00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Let's look at the foundational concepts of project management.

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Let's first look at what is a project.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:12,000
According to the PIMBOK Guide, a project is a temporary endeavor

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,000
undertaken to create a unique product, service, or result.

5
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Temporary means that a project has definite start and end dates.

6
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Projects are taken up for a definite period to create value, drive change,

7
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,000
and deliver business value.

8
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:35,000
Here are a few examples of projects developing a new product,

9
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:39,000
constructing a building, merging two organizations,

10
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:45,000
developing a new software application, erecting and commissioning a manufacturing plant,

11
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:50,000
upgrading an existing product, developing a new service.

12
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Temporary projects come to an end when the objectives have been met,

13
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:00,000
or the objectives can no longer be met to defectors such as,

14
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
lack of a business need, unavailability of funding,

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,000
changes in organizational priorities or strategy, changes in the external environment,

16
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:17,000
the project is aborted or forcefully closed when the objectives can no longer be met.

17
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Let us talk about the critical success factors of a project.

18
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
The success of a project depends on several factors, including,

19
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,000
definition of the core problem and the needs of the project,

20
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:37,000
the organization's ability and maturity in project management,

21
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
availability of resources, skill levels of the team members,

22
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:45,000
availability of funding, and collaboration and communication

23
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:48,000
among project stakeholders.

24
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Successful project management includes understanding project management concepts

25
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:58,000
and being able to adapt and apply them to the individual project.

26
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
Let's now look at the factors leading to the failure of projects.

27
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:07,000
Research has identified the following top reasons for project failures,

28
00:02:07,000 --> 00:02:11,000
ambiguous, misunderstood or incorrect requirements,

29
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:15,000
lack of control over project costs and schedules,

30
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
scoop creep, minimal involvement of sponsors in the project strategy and direction,

31
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:27,000
not existent, out-of-date, incomplete or poorly constructed project plan,

32
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:32,000
frequently changing project managers, unclear responsibilities and relationships

33
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,000
among project teams, both internal and external,

34
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,000
lack of clarity regarding project benefits and deliverables,

35
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
poor or no-change control, inappropriate or insufficient skills.

36
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Let us take a look at project life cycles and their development approach.

37
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
In a broad sense, there are three methodologies for project management.

38
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:07,000
The predictive or planned-driven method often referred to as the traditional waterfall approach.

39
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:12,000
The agile method, a more modern and adaptive approach.

40
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:18,000
The hybrid method, which combines elements of both waterfall and agile approaches.

41
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:24,000
The predictive or planned-driven approach is also referred to as the waterfall life cycle.

42
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
This approach is taken in those projects where the requirements are predetermined

43
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:34,000
and are not likely to change as changes may increase costs significantly.

44
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:41,000
An example of the predictive or planned-driven approach is the construction of an apartment complex.

45
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:46,000
The project manager plays a crucial role in ensuring a successful project.

46
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:51,000
When the project is completed, the deliverables are transitioned to the customer

47
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:56,000
and the value is realized both in the short and long term.

48
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:02,000
An agile approach is recommended in those complex projects where the end product is not known

49
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
and there could be frequent changes.

50
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
The coordination of the customer and the team drives the project forward.

51
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
An example of an agile approach is a pharmaceutical research project or a project to develop software.

52
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
The product owner controls the value proposition and delivery.

53
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:25,000
The team works on and delivers the product or solution.

54
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The scrum master or agile coach facilitates throughout the cycle.

55
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:36,000
A hybrid approach is a combination of waterfall and agile approaches.

56
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:41,000
This approach is recommended in projects where some requirements are known and fixed

57
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:47,000
in certain areas of the project, while new methods or techniques could be tried in other areas

58
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,000
within the same project.

59
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:54,000
The team might switch approaches based on the changing work requirements or circumstances.

60
00:04:54,000 --> 00:05:01,000
Projects can be predominantly predictive while using some agile components or predominantly agile

61
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:04,000
using some predictive components.

62
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,000
An example of a hybrid approach is designing a spacecraft.

63
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:12,000
Let's now understand what a development lifecycle means.

64
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:18,000
It is the cost-effective and time-efficient process that development teams use to design

65
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
and build high-quality products.

66
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,000
The development of a product in a project can follow a predictive lifecycle, an iterative lifecycle,

67
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:35,000
an incremental lifecycle, an adaptive lifecycle, and a hybrid lifecycle, a predictive lifecycle.

68
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Here, the project scope, time, and cost are determined as early as possible.

69
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:45,000
The changes to the project scope are carefully managed.

70
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:49,000
It is also referred to as the waterfall lifecycle.

71
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
An iterative lifecycle.

72
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,000
In this model, the scope is determined earlier, but the time at cost estimates are regularly modified

73
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:02,000
as the understanding of the product increases.

74
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,000
An incremental lifecycle.

75
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:11,000
Here, the deliverable is produced through a series of iterations that successfully add functionality.

76
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
An adaptive lifecycle.

77
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Here, projects can be agile, iterative, or incremental.

78
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:22,000
The scope is defined and approved before the start of an iteration.

79
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:27,000
It is also referred to as agile or change-driven lifecycle.

80
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,000
The iterations are rapid and have fixed duration and cost.

81
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:34,000
A hybrid lifecycle.

82
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:40,000
A hybrid lifecycle is a combination of a predictive and an adaptive lifecycle.

83
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:44,000
How does the iterative and incremental approach help?

84
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:51,000
These involve phases that are intentionally repeated as the team keeps on knowing their deliverables better.

85
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:57,000
It is a good practice to use iterative and incremental practices throughout the project lifecycle,

86
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,000
as it will help the project team to increase the clarity in requirements,

87
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:05,000
make estimates more accurate and reduce risks.

88
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:17,000
Let us explore the concept of a project management office.

89
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:25,000
A project management office, PMO, is an organizational structure that standardizes project-related governance processes

90
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:31,000
and facilitates the sharing of resources, methodologies, tools, and techniques.

91
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:37,000
The three types of PMO are supportive, controlling, and directive.

92
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:44,000
The supportive PMO's focus on developing best practices, methodologies, standards, and templates.

93
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:49,000
They also coach mentor, train, and guide project managers.

94
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:56,000
Whereas, controlling PMOs are responsible for monitoring compliance with project management standards,

95
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:01,000
policies, procedures, and templates through project audits.

96
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Likewise, directive PMOs manage shared resources and facilitate communication between various projects.

97
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:16,000
Remember that the level of control varies depending on the type of PMO structure in organizations.

98
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:24,000
The supportive PMO involves low control, the controlling PMO involves medium control,

99
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:28,000
and the directive PMO involves high control.

100
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:36,000
Furthermore, some organizations have agile centers of excellence, also known as value delivery office.

101
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:43,000
The role of an agile centers of excellence is to enable the project teams by coaching and mentoring,

102
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:53,000
rather than managing them, and build agile mindset, skills, and capabilities throughout the organization.

103
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:04,000
Let's understand what organizational project management or OPM means.

104
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:12,000
OPM is a strategy execution framework that coordinates project, program, portfolio, and operations management,

105
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:16,000
and which enables organizations to deliver a strategy.

106
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
Project management enables the achievement of organizational goals and objectives.

107
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:29,000
Program management harmonizes its program components, and controls interdependencies to realize specified benefits.

108
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:37,000
Portfolio management aligns portfolios with organizational strategies by selecting the right programs or projects,

109
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:41,000
prioritizing the work, and providing the needed resources.

110
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:47,000
And finally, operations management includes an organization's day-to-day operations,

111
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:57,000
and when all the above are strategically managed, they combine to create OPM.

112
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:04,000
Let us now understand the relationship between projects, programs, and portfolios.

113
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:10,000
According to the Project Management Institute, a guide to the project management body of knowledge,

114
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:20,000
PIMBOK Guide, Sixth Edition, a program is a group of related projects, subsidiary programs, and program activities that are managed in a

115
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:35,000
coordinated manner to obtain benefits not available from managing them individually.

116
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:46,000
A portfolio is a collection of projects, programs, subsidiary portfolios, and operations managed as a group to achieve strategic objectives.

117
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:52,000
The image here shows the relation between portfolios, programs, and projects.

118
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:57,000
A portfolio represents a portion of an organization's overall strategy.

119
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:02,000
The strategic goals are cascaded down to lower-level components.

120
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:12,000
A portfolio may contain programs, projects, and also other work.

121
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
Let's explore the concept of organizational structures.

122
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:21,000
Let us now understand how an organizational structure affects a project.

123
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:30,000
The organizational structure plays a critical role in determining how different groups and individuals within the organization interact.

124
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:38,000
It also impacts the authority of the project manager, resource availability, and the way the projects are carried out.

125
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:51,000
Let's examine the various types of organizational structures, including functional structure, matrix structure, project-oriented structure, and composite structure.

126
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Let us start with the functional structure.

127
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:59,000
Organizations with a functional structure share the following characteristics.

128
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:05,000
Resources are grouped based on carrying out specific, similar sets of activities.

129
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:12,000
Reporting is hierarchical, with individuals reporting to their functional head, the functional manager.

130
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
The project manager has lower authority compared to the functional manager.

131
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:23,000
In a matrix structure, resources are drawn from other functional areas.

132
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:31,000
They report to multiple managers, the functional manager, their resource manager, and possibly to the project manager.

133
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:41,000
The structure may be characterized as weak, balanced, or strong, depending on the relative authority of the project manager to the functional manager.

134
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:53,000
The project-oriented structure is characterized by the project manager and a core project team that operate as a separate organizational unit within the parent organization.

135
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:59,000
Resources are 100% dedicated to the project and report to the project manager.

136
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:05,000
The project manager has a significant amount of authority and independence.

137
00:13:05,000 --> 00:13:16,000
All organizational structures, including functional, matrix, and project-oriented structures at various levels of an organization, are considered composite structures.

138
