359
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:29,000
Describe the components of governance.

360
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:37,000
Differentiate between predictive and adaptive project approaches to understand their influence on project progression.

361
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:54,000
Evaluate the importance of reviews and project environments to recognize their impact on value improvement and decision making for project advancement.

362
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:58,000
Let's learn what project governance is and its components.

363
00:46:58,000 --> 00:47:13,000
Project governance is the framework, functions and processes that guide project management activities in order to create a unique product, service or result that meets organizational, strategic and operational goals.

364
00:47:14,000 --> 00:47:24,000
Identifying a governance structure is crucial for a project. Each project is unique in terms of requirements, risks and stakeholders among others.

365
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:29,000
Depending on the project complexities, the governance structure could vary.

366
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:34,000
The structure is aligned with the organizational strategy and risk tolerances.

367
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:38,000
Let's look at the complements of a project governance framework.

368
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:48,000
As stated in the PIMBOC guide, a project governance framework can include project success and deliverable acceptance criteria.

369
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:52,000
The process to identify, escalate and resolve issues.

370
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:58,000
The relationship between the project team, organizational groups and external stakeholders.

371
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:07,000
The project organization chart with the project roles, communication processes and procedures, processes for project decision making.

372
00:48:07,000 --> 00:48:12,000
Guidelines for aligning project governance and organizational strategy.

373
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:17,000
The project lifecycle approach. The process for stage date or phase reviews.

374
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:23,000
The process for the review and approval of changes above the project manager's authority.

375
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:29,000
And the process to align internal stakeholders with the project process requirements.

376
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:40,000
Let's look at the guidelines for good project governance.

377
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:47,000
These guidelines are involve the organization's decision makers who are frequently at senior managers.

378
00:48:47,000 --> 00:48:52,000
Choose the most appropriate governance goals and try to keep them simple.

379
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:58,000
Select a group of experienced individuals to be responsible for all governance activities.

380
00:48:58,000 --> 00:49:02,000
Practice governance for projects, programs and portfolios.

381
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:07,000
Keep the governance process transparent to the project stakeholders.

382
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:16,000
And finally, remember that governance is an evolutionary process and take advantage of the lessons you have learned during this process.

383
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:19,000
Let us now understand the escalation procedure.

384
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:28,000
Escalation is the process of addressing issues or problems that fall beyond the authority of the project manager or the team.

385
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:32,000
When an issue falls within the defined threshold, the team will handle it.

386
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:40,000
If it exceeds the threshold, it gets escalated to the appropriate stakeholder for a decision and further action.

387
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:56,000
It's crucial to have well-defined escalation procedures and team members should be familiar with these processes to ensure timely responses.

388
00:49:56,000 --> 00:50:02,000
Let's explore how to apply governance to various types of projects.

389
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:19,000
According to PIMBOX 6th edition, at the beginning of each phase, it is a good practice to verify and validate the assumptions made before the project has begun, analyze the risks, and explain in detail the processes required to achieve the deliverables.

390
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:29,000
After the key deliverables of a particular phase are produced, a review at the end of the phase is necessary to ensure completeness and acceptance.

391
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:47,000
What is a phase gate? A phase gate, also known as a governance gate, tall gate or kill point, is a review at the end of a phase in which a decision is made to continue to the next phase as is, to continue with some modification or to end a project or program.

392
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:55,000
Each review is used to check if each phase has fulfilled the exit criteria and is eligible to move to the next phase.

393
00:50:55,000 --> 00:51:00,000
These criteria serve as thresholds for the continuation of the project.

394
00:51:00,000 --> 00:51:12,000
Software development projects can utilize a special type of phase gate called a quality gate, which is located before a phase that is strongly dependent upon the outcomes of a previous phase.

395
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:40,000
When it comes to adaptive projects, the process of applying governance includes the following steps, splitting work into releases, reviewing results at the end of iterations, gathering feedback and taking action to improve value in the next iteration, continuing until the customer's acceptance criteria, for example, definition of done or MVP are satisfied or the project ends.

396
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:57,000
Let us now quickly recap this lesson. Project governance is a framework that provides oversight of processes and procedures, guiding project management activities to achieve objectives.

397
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:05,000
Governance encompasses processes for a life cycle approach, phase reviews, success and deliverable acceptance criteria.

398
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:15,000
Governance also includes identification, escalation and resolution of issues and approval of changes beyond the project manager's authority.

399
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:24,000
In predictive projects, a review at the end of a phase, known as the phase gate review, determines the transition to the next phase.

400
00:52:24,000 --> 00:52:34,000
In adaptive projects, a review is conducted at the end of each iteration, and based on the feedback received, improvements are planned for the subsequent iteration.

